 idioms of violence inscribed in these socialization rites help produce educated, moral persons but in ways that trouble Tibetans who aspire to modernity. Bringing the study of language and social interaction to our understanding of Buddhism for the first time, Lempert shows and why liberal ideals are being acted out by monks in India, offering a provocative alternative view of liberalism as a globalizing discourse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBuddhist monasticism and religious ordersxEducationxChinaxTibet Autonomous Region. 0aBuddhist monasticism and religious ordersxEducationzChinazTibet Autonomous Region. 0aBuddhist monasticism and religious ordersxEducationzIndia. 0aDisciplinexReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aLiberalism (Religion)xIndia. 0aLiberalism (Religion)zIndia. 0aTibetansxReligionxIndia. 0aTibetanszIndiaxReligion. 0aViolencexReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520952010423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520952010.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles